<h2>Solar Panels in Michigan</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>Michigan's solar resource potential often surprises homeowners who assume the state's northern location and variable weather patterns make solar energy impractical. In reality, Michigan receives approximately 4.0 peak sun hours daily on average, with southern regions of the state experiencing up to 4.5 peak sun hours during optimal months. This solar irradiance is sufficient to generate substantial electricity savings, particularly when systems are properly sized and oriented. The state's peak solar production months from May through September align well with increased air conditioning usage, creating natural efficiency in energy consumption patterns.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in Michigan can produce between 1,100 to 1,400 kilowatt-hours per installed kilowatt annually, depending on system orientation, shading, and local weather patterns. South-facing installations with minimal shading perform optimally, though east and west-facing arrays can achieve 85-90% of south-facing production. Even during Michigan's cloudier winter months, modern solar panels continue generating electricity, with snow typically sliding off tilted panels or melting quickly due to the panels' dark surface absorbing available sunlight.</p>

<p>The state's net metering policies through DTE Energy and other utilities allow homeowners to bank excess summer production as credits to offset winter consumption when solar production naturally decreases. This annual balancing effect means properly sized systems can offset 80-100% of a home's electrical usage over a full year, despite seasonal variations. Michigan's moderate temperatures also benefit solar panel efficiency, as photovoltaic cells perform better in cooler conditions compared to extremely hot climates where panels can lose efficiency due to excessive heat.</p>

