<h2>HVAC Systems in Michigan</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Michigan's continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment capable of handling both frigid winter temperatures that can drop below -10¬∞F and humid summer conditions reaching 85-90¬∞F. The state experiences approximately 6,500-7,500 heating degree days annually, indicating substantial heating requirements, while also accumulating 600-900 cooling degree days during summer months. This dual-season demand necessitates HVAC systems designed for year-round efficiency rather than single-season optimization.</p>

<p>Winter heating loads dominate Michigan's energy consumption patterns, with natural gas furnaces traditionally serving as the primary heating source for most homes. However, modern heat pump technology has evolved to remain efficient even in sub-freezing temperatures, making air-source and ground-source heat pumps increasingly viable options. Cold-climate heat pumps can operate effectively down to -15¬∞F, providing both heating and cooling from a single system while significantly reducing energy consumption compared to traditional furnace and air conditioner combinations.</p>

<p>Summer cooling demands in Michigan require careful attention to humidity control alongside temperature management. The state's proximity to the Great Lakes creates humid conditions that can make temperatures feel warmer than actual readings. Properly sized air conditioning systems with appropriate SEER ratings ensure efficient cooling while maintaining indoor humidity levels between 30-50% for optimal comfort. Variable-speed systems particularly excel in Michigan's climate by adjusting output to match real-time conditions rather than cycling on and off frequently.</p>

