<h2>Michigan Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Michigan homeowners benefit from a comprehensive array of incentives and rebates that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) allows homeowners to deduct 30% of solar installation costs from their federal taxes, with no cap on the credit amount. This incentive applies to the complete system cost, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor. The 30% credit rate remains in effect through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034, making current installations particularly advantageous.</p>

<p>At the state level, Michigan offers a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, ensuring that the added home value from solar installations doesn't increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both the equipment and installation value, providing ongoing savings throughout the system's lifespan. Additionally, Michigan does not impose sales tax on solar equipment purchases, further reducing upfront costs for homeowners.</p>

<p>DTE Energy provides various rebate programs for energy efficiency improvements, including rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems, smart thermostats, and energy-efficient appliances. The utility's Home Energy Efficiency program offers rebates up to \$500 for qualifying furnaces and air conditioners, while their heat pump rebates can reach \$1,000 for cold-climate models. DTE's net metering program allows solar customers to receive full retail credit for excess electricity generated, with credits rolling over monthly and paid out annually at avoided cost rates. Consumers Energy, serving western Michigan, offers similar rebate programs and net metering arrangements, ensuring statewide coverage for energy efficiency incentives.</p>

<p>Additional financing options include Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) programs available in select Michigan municipalities, allowing homeowners to finance solar and efficiency improvements through property tax assessments. Many local utilities also offer on-bill financing programs that enable customers to pay for upgrades through their monthly utility bills, often with terms that ensure immediate positive cash flow from energy savings.</p>

